Help Type: topic
Topic: runtime

Runtime Behavior

Archive-first streams:
  - `wikigraph <archive-uri> create --input-format markdown|txt` reads source text from stdin.
  - `wikigraph <archive-uri> export --output-format markdown|txt` can write text projections to stdout.
  - `wikigraph transform --input-format markdown|txt --output-format markdown|txt` runs direct one-shot stream digest/export.
  - Retrieval commands print human-readable text by default and support `--json` where documented.
  - A bare `wikigraph` in an interactive terminal prints root help.
  - A bare non-interactive `wikigraph` invocation is not a transform shortcut; use `wikigraph transform`.

Exit behavior:
  - Success returns exit code 0.
  - Failures return non-zero.
  - Commands that accept `--json` or `--jsonl` emit machine-readable error objects when those flags are present.
  - Commands without machine-readable output support print plain-text errors.

Queue behavior:
  - Reading Graph, Reading Summary, and Knowledge Graph generation run as device-local queue jobs.
  - Queue generation jobs consume LLM tokens, may incur provider charges, and can run for minutes to hours on large archives.
  - `queue add` requires `--accept-cost` as an explicit cost/time acknowledgement.
  - The queue state lives under `~/.wikigraph/state`.
  - `queue add`, `wkg-job://<job-id> resume`, `wkg-job://<job-id> boost`, and `wkg-job://<job-id>/target set` try to start a transient worker.
  - The worker exits after idle time; it is not intended to be a permanent daemon.
  - `wkg-job://<job-id> watch --jsonl` is the stable agent-facing progress stream.
  - `request.concurrent` in `~/.wikigraph/config.json` controls the worker slot count.

Progress and diagnostics:
  - Queue progress is recorded as durable events and exposed by `queue watch`.
  - `progress_snapshot` events include reading-graph words, reading-summary words, and approximate output tokens.
  - `transform --verbose` writes diagnostic logs to stderr.

Workspace behavior:
  - Archive creation from URL or stdin uses temporary workspaces.
  - `transform --digest-dir <path>` uses the provided digest workspace for source digest runs.
  - Queue jobs use state-managed workspaces.
  - Succeeded jobs delete their workspace by default.
  - Failed and canceled jobs keep their workspace for debugging until cleanup.

In-place archive edits:
  - Mutating `.wikg` commands go through the archive coordinator.
  - Active queue jobs block destructive chapter maintenance edits for the same chapter.
  - Archive writes are coordinated through local state and flushed through managed workspaces.

